data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed for this code.**

Your `SimpleWorker` class only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no references to `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`, so the code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Task.WhenAll(items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item))));
}
```

This is a stylistic improvement — not a migration requirement.
